# Iteration loop

The full prose version with a worked example lives in [CONTRIBUTING.md](../../CONTRIBUTING.md). This rule is the enforceable short version. Agents follow it on every change.

## Branching

- Branch off `main`. Never commit to `main`.
- Names: `feat/<slug>`, `fix/<slug>`, `chore/<slug>`, `docs/<slug>`.
- One concern per branch and per PR. If you find a second thing, open a follow-up branch.

## Before writing code

1. State the goal in one sentence. If you cannot, the scope is wrong; stop and clarify.
2. Locate the PRD section and ADR(s) the change touches. Link them in the PR body.
3. If the change conflicts with the PRD or an ADR, write the ADR (or PRD update) **first**, in the same PR. Do not silently bend the spec to fit the code.
4. List the test IDs from `docs/testing.md` the change must pass or add.

## While coding

- Keep config fixes (env vars, Docker, infra) in a separate PR from product code.
- If a deployment problem forces a code change, that code change still needs a test. No "temporary" relaxations of validation, schema, or scope checks.
- Do-not-touch zones (see [AGENTS.md](../../AGENTS.md)) require an ADR or PRD update in the same PR. Call it out in the PR body.

## Before pushing

```bash
make ci
```

Push only when green. CI is the last gate before review, not a remote linter.

## Pull request

- Use the [PR template](../../.github/pull_request_template.md). Fill every section.
- Self-review the diff in GitHub before requesting a reviewer.
- Squash-merge. Delete the branch.

## Working as an AI agent in this repo

- Produce a written plan before code on anything bigger than a one-file change.
- Never silently change scope, weaken validation, or skip tests. If you discover the spec is wrong, stop and write the ADR.
- Pick model strength by risk: stronger model for auth, authz, audit, migrations, and any do-not-touch zone; default model for UI, copy, and isolated logic.
- If you start looping or drifting from the spec, end the session. Write what you learned to `HANDOFF.md`. Start a new session with a tighter prompt.

